Murray says that couriers could be engaged on the Continent but also in London (specifically, No. 7, Old Compton Street, Soho; or No. 11, Panton Square); 
                    and evidently Salvador was based in London, as Ruskin mentions in February 1835 that the courier visited Herne Hill to help plan the route for the 
                    Tour of 1835 
                    (Handbook for Travellers on the Continent, xix; 
                    Burd, ed., Ruskin Family Letters, 297).
